    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:77ce40e1-c111-4720-8bf4-156ffa4cf1c2",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old woman who comes to clinic because of persistent myalgia [SNOMED:M79.1] with a dull, aching soreness in her shoulders, upper back, and thighs. She says the muscles feel heavy and tender, with occasional pinching episodes and intermittent cramps, especially in her thighs and calves toward the end of the day [SNOMED:M79.1, MEDDIALOG:M79.1:1]. The discomfort has been present on and off for months and leaves her feeling worn down by the end of the workday. She appears tired but not acutely ill, sits carefully, and shifts position during the interview because prolonged sitting aggravates the aching [MEDDIALOG:M79.1:1]. On examination, the affected muscle groups are tender to palpation without joint swelling or focal neurologic deficit.\n\nShe works as an office administrator in Brno and spends much of the day at a computer, which she feels makes the aching more noticeable by late afternoon. Outside work she tries to stay active with short walks and light stretching, but she has cut back on longer bike rides and weekend gardening because repetitive digging, lifting pots, and riding uphill tend to leave her muscles more sore and crampy afterward [SNOMED:M79.1]. She lives with her husband, keeps close contact with her adult daughter, and says her family has noticed that she has become less social on painful days because she is uncomfortable rather than depressed [SNOMED:M79.1].\n\n{patientName} says the pain is in the muscles rather than the joints and denies any visible injury. She worries because routine blood work in the past was unrevealing, similar to experiences described in patients with muscle aches where prior evaluation can be nondiagnostic [MEDDIALOG:M79.1:4]. She has no focal neurologic deficits on presentation and is mainly concerned about the ongoing muscle pain itself [SNOMED:M79.1]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ddc66007-b72c-41e7-89ab-917493aba2bd",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of hypertension and type 2 diabetes treated chronically with amlodipine and metformin. She also uses cetirizine seasonally for allergic rhinitis. She reports that the muscle aches developed gradually over several months and are more noticeable after physically demanding weekends in the garden or longer bicycle rides. She has not had recent fever, major trauma, or known rheumatologic disease, and previous basic blood work was described to her as normal despite ongoing muscle aches, reflecting that prior investigations may be clear in patients presenting with myalgia-like complaints [MEDDIALOG:M79.1:4]. She has not required hospitalization for this problem. She is a nonsmoker, drinks alcohol only occasionally, and notes that long periods of sitting tend to worsen the discomfort [MEDDIALOG:M79.1:1]."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
